menu "MQTT Relay"

    config MQTT_RELAY_KEEPALIVE_SEC
        int "MQTT keepalive interval (seconds)"
        default 60
        range 15 3600
        help
            How often the ESP32 sends a PINGREQ to the broker when idle.
            This keeps the TCP connection alive through NAT timeouts and
            tells the broker that the client is still alive.

            60 seconds is a good default.  Reduce if your broker or
            network has aggressive NAT timeout rules.

    config MQTT_RELAY_RECONNECT_TIMEOUT_MS
        int "MQTT reconnect timeout (ms)"
        default 5000
        range 1000 60000
        help
            Time the esp_mqtt_client waits before attempting to reconnect
            after a disconnection.  The client handles reconnection
            automatically; this controls the backoff delay.

    config MQTT_RELAY_TASK_STACK_KB
        int "MQTT client internal task stack size (KB)"
        default 8
        range 2 16
        help
            Stack size for the esp_mqtt_client internal FreeRTOS task.
            This is the task that calls mqtt_event_handler for every event.
            In the HARDENED build the handler runs TOTP (mbedTLS), opens a
            UDP socket, and calls esp_mqtt_client_publish — a deep call chain
            that requires at least 8 KB. 4 KB will cause a stack overflow.

    config MQTT_RELAY_SKIP_CERT_CN_CHECK
        bool "Skip TLS certificate common name check"
        default n
        help
            When enabled, the ESP32 does not verify that the broker's
            TLS certificate common name matches the broker hostname.
            This also disables TLS Server Name Indication (SNI), so it
            should not be used with hosted MQTT brokers such as HiveMQ
            Cloud.

            Enable only for loopback/debug brokers where hostname
            authentication and SNI are intentionally unnecessary.

    config WOL_LEGACY_RSP_TOPIC
        bool "Also publish to legacy /r response topic (backward compatibility)"
        default y
        help
            When enabled, all status messages are ALSO published to the
            old single response topic (wol/<mac>/r or the HARDENED
            equivalent without suffix) in addition to the new /s topic.

            Disable once all MQTT consumers have been updated to subscribe
            to the /s and /l topics instead.

    config WOL_GPIO_COMMANDS
        bool "Enable GPIO output control via MQTT"
        default n
        help
            When enabled, the relay accepts GPIO control commands on the
            same command topic as WoL commands. GPIO commands use a JSON
            payload with "action":"gpio". In HARDENED builds a valid TOTP
            code must also be present under a "totp" key.

            Payload format:
              STANDARD:  {"action":"gpio","pin":4,"level":1}
              HARDENED:  {"action":"gpio","pin":4,"level":1,"totp":123456}

    config WOL_GPIO_ALLOWED_PINS
        string "Comma-separated list of GPIO pins allowed for MQTT control"
        default "4,5"
        depends on WOL_GPIO_COMMANDS
        help
            Only pins listed here can be set via MQTT. This prevents a
            misconfigured or malicious command from toggling strapping pins
            (GPIO 0, 2, 12, 15) or UART/Flash pins.

            Default: GPIO 4 and GPIO 5 (safe general-purpose outputs).
            Example: "4,5,16,17"

endmenu
